# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aqueduct-bridge
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] A **100-year flood**, also called a **1% flood**, or **High Probability** in the UK, is a flood event for a defined location at a level reached or exceeded once per hundred years, on average, but as there are many locations there are multiple independent 100-year floods within the same year.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] In the US, it is estimated on past records as having a 1 in 100 chance (1% probability) of being equaled or exceeded in any given year.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] The estimated boundaries of inundation in a 100-year or 1% flood are marked on flood maps.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] UK planning guidance defines Flood Zone 3a "High Probability" as Land having a 1% or greater annual probability of river flooding; or Land having a 0.5% or greater annual probability of sea.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] For coastal flooding and lake flooding, a 100-year flood is generally expressed as a water level elevation or depth, and includes a combination of tide, storm surge, and waves.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] For river systems, a 100-year flood can be expressed as a flow rate, from which the flood elevation is derived.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] The resulting area of inundation is referred to as the *100-year floodplain*.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] Estimates of the 100-year flood flow rate and other streamflow statistics for any stream in the United States are available.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] A 100-year storm may or may not cause a 100-year flood, because of rainfall timing and location variations among different drainage basins, and independent causes of floods, such as snow melt and ice dams.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] In the UK, the Environment Agency publishes a comprehensive map of all areas at risk of a 100-year flood.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] In the US, the Federal Emergency Management Agency publishes maps of the 100-year and 500-year floodplains.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] Maps of the riverine or coastal 100-year floodplain may figure importantly in building permits, environmental regulations, and flood insurance.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] These analyses generally represent 20th-century climate and may underestimate the effects of climate change.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] A common misunderstanding is that a 100-year flood happens once in a 100-year period.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] On average one happens per 100 years, five per 500 years, ten per thousand years.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] In any particular 100 years at one spot, there is a 37% chance that no 100-year flood happens, 37% chance that exactly one happens, and 26% chance that two or more happen.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] On the Danube River at Passau, Germany, the actual intervals between 100-year floods during 1501 to 2013 ranged from 37 to 192 years.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] A related misunderstanding is that floods bigger than 100-year floods are too rare to be of concern.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] The 1% chance per year accumulates to 10% chance per decade, 26% chance during a 30-year mortgage, and 55% chance during an 80-year human lifetime.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] It is common to refer to 100-year floods as floods with 1% chance per year.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] It is equally true to refer to them as floods with 10% chance per decade.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] Over a large diverse area, such as a large country or the world, in an average year 1% of watersheds have 100-year floods or bigger, and 0.1% of watersheds have 1,000-year floods or bigger.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] There are more in wet years, fewer in dry years.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] Of 1.6 million kilometers of coastline in the world, in an average year 1,600 kilometers have 1,000-year floods or bigger, more in stormy years, fewer in calmer years.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] In 2017 the Netherlands designed some areas against million-year floods.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] The American Society of Civil Engineers recommends designing some structures for up to 1,000-year floods, while it recommends designing for up to 3,000-year winds.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] Per century, any one area has a 63% chance of a 100-year flood or worse, 10% chance of a 1,000-year flood, 1% chance of a 10,000-year flood, and 0.01% chance of a million-year flood.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] In the United States, the 100-year flood provides the risk basis for flood insurance rates.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] A *regulatory flood* or *base flood* is routinely established for river reaches through a science-based rule-making process targeted to a 100-year flood at the historical average recurrence interval.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] In addition to historical flood data, the process accounts for previously established regulatory values, the effects of flood-control reservoirs, and changes in land use in the watershed.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] Coastal flood hazards have been mapped by a similar approach that includes the relevant physical processes.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] Most areas where serious floods can occur in the United States have been mapped consistently in this manner.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] On average nationwide, those 100-year flood estimates are sufficient for the purposes of the National Flood Insurance Program (NFIP) and offer reasonable estimates of future flood risk, if the future is like the past.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] Approximately 3% of the U.S. population lives in areas subject to the 1% annual chance coastal flood hazard.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] In theory, removing homes and businesses from areas that flood repeatedly can protect people and reduce insurance losses, but in practice it is difficult for people to retreat from established neighborhoods.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] where *T* is the threshold mean recurrence interval (e.g.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] If T is in years, then *n* is the number of years in the period, and Pe is the chance per year, Annual Exceedance Probability.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] The probability of exceedance *Pe* is also described as the natural, inherent, or hydrologic risk of failure.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] However, the expected value of the number of 100-year floods occurring in any 100-year period is 1.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] Ten-year floods have a 10% chance of occurring in any given year (Pe =0.10); 500-year floods have a 0.2% chance of occurring in any given year (Pe =0.002); etc.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] The percent chance of a T-year flood occurring in a single year is 100/T, where T is bigger than 1.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] The same formula above can give the chance of occurrence in less than a year.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] A 1-year flood is a 12-month flood, with a 1/12 chance each month, and the formula in months shows 65% chance each year.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] The field of extreme value theory was created to model rare events such as 100-year floods for the purposes of civil engineering.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] This theory is most commonly applied to the maximum or minimum observed stream flows of a given river.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] In desert areas where there are only ephemeral washes, this method is applied to the maximum observed flow over a given period of time (24-hours, 6-hours, or 3-hours).
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] The extreme value analysis only considers the most extreme event observed in a given year.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] So, between the large spring runoff and a heavy summer rain storm, whichever resulted in more runoff would be considered the extreme event, while the smaller event would be ignored in the analysis (even though both may have been capable of causing terrible flooding in their own right).
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] There are a number of assumptions that are made to complete the analysis that determines the 100-year flood.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] First, the extreme events observed in each year must be independent from year to year.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] In other words, the maximum river flow rate from 1984 cannot be found to be significantly correlated with the observed flow rate in 1985, which cannot be correlated with 1986, and so forth.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] The second assumption is that the observed extreme events must come from the same probability density function.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] The third assumption is that the probability distribution relates to the largest storm (rainfall or river flow rate measurement) that occurs in any one year.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] The fourth assumption is that the probability distribution function is stationary, meaning that the mean (average), standard deviation and maximum and minimum values are not increasing or decreasing over time.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] This concept is referred to as stationarity.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] The first assumption is often but not always valid and should be tested on a case-by-case basis.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] The second assumption is often valid if the extreme events are observed under similar climate conditions.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] For example, if the extreme events on record all come from late summer thunderstorms (as is the case in the southwest U.S.), or from snow pack melting (as is the case in north-central U.S.), then this assumption should be valid.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] If, however, there are some extreme events taken from thunder storms, others from snow pack melting, and others from hurricanes, then this assumption is most likely not valid.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] The third assumption is only a problem when trying to forecast a low, but maximum flow event (for example, an event smaller than a 2-year flood).
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] Since this is not typically a goal in extreme analysis, or in civil engineering design, then the situation rarely presents itself.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] The final assumption about stationarity is difficult to test from data for a single site because of the large uncertainties in even the longest flood records (see next section).
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] More broadly, substantial evidence of climate change strongly suggests that the probability distribution is also changing and that managing flood risks in the future will become even more difficult.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] The simplest implication of this is that most of the historical data represent 20th-century climate and might not be valid for extreme event analysis in the 21st century.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] When these assumptions are violated, there is an *unknown* amount of uncertainty introduced into the reported value of what the 100-year flood means in terms of rainfall intensity, or flood depth.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] When all of the inputs are known, the uncertainty can be measured in the form of a confidence interval.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] For example, one might say there is a 95% chance that the 100-year flood is greater than X, but less than Y.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] Direct statistical analysis to estimate the 100-year riverine flood is possible only at the relatively few locations where an annual series of maximum instantaneous flood discharges has been recorded.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] In the United States as of 2014, taxpayers have supported such records for at least 60 years at fewer than 2,600 locations, for at least 90 years at fewer than 500, and for at least 120 years at only 11.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] For comparison, the total area of the nation is about 3,800,000 square miles (9,800,000 km2), so there are perhaps 3,000 stream reaches that drain watersheds of 1,000 square miles (2,600 km2) and 300,000 reaches that drain 10 square miles (26 km2).
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] In urban areas, 100-year flood estimates are needed for watersheds as small as 1 square mile (2.6 km2).
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] For reaches without sufficient data for direct analysis, 100-year flood estimates are derived from indirect statistical analysis of flood records at other locations in a hydrologically similar region or from other hydrologic models.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] Similarly for coastal floods, tide gauge data exist for only about 1,450 sites worldwide, of which only about 950 added information to the global data center between January 2010 and March 2016.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] Much longer records of flood elevations exist at a few locations around the world, such as the Danube River at Passau, Germany, but they must be evaluated carefully for accuracy and completeness before any statistical interpretation.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] For an individual stream reach, the uncertainties in any analysis can be large, so 100-year flood estimates have large individual uncertainties for most stream reaches.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] For the largest recorded flood at any specific location, or any potentially larger event, the recurrence interval always is poorly known.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] Spatial variability adds more uncertainty, because a flood peak observed at different locations on the same stream during the same event commonly represents a different recurrence interval at each location.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] If an extreme storm drops enough rain on one branch of a river to cause a 100-year flood, but no rain falls over another branch, the flood wave downstream from their junction might have a recurrence interval of only 10 years.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] Conversely, a storm that produces a 25-year flood simultaneously in each branch might form a 100-year flood downstream.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] During a time of flooding, news accounts necessarily simplify the story by reporting the greatest damage and largest recurrence interval estimated at any location.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] The public can easily and incorrectly conclude that the recurrence interval applies to all stream reaches in the flood area.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] Peak elevations of 14 floods as early as 1501 on the Danube River at Passau, Germany, reveal great variability in the actual intervals between floods.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] Flood events greater than the 50-year flood occurred at intervals of 4 to 192 years since 1501, and the 50-year flood of 2002 was followed only 11 years later by a 500-year flood.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] Only half of the intervals between 50- and 100-year floods were within 50 percent of the nominal average interval.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/100-year-flood] Similarly, the intervals between 5-year floods during 1955 to 2007 ranged from 5 months to 16 years, and only half were within 2.5 to 7.5 years.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/abrasion-geology] Abrasion, under its strictest definition, is commonly confused with attrition and sometimes hydraulic action however, the latter less commonly so.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/abrasion-geology] Both abrasion and attrition refers to the wearing down of an object.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/abrasion-geology] Abrasion occurs as a result of two surfaces rubbing against each other, resulting in the wearing down of one or both of the surfaces.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/abrasion-geology] However, attrition refers to the breaking off of particles (erosion) which occurs as a result of objects hitting against each other.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/abrasion-geology] Abrasion leads to surface-level destruction over a period of time, whereas attrition results in more change at a faster rate.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/abrasion-geology] Today, the geomorphology community uses the term "abrasion" in a looser way, often interchangeably with the term "wear".
[src:aqueduct-bridge/abrasion-geology] Abrasion in a stream or river channel occurs when the sediment carried by a river scours the bed and banks, contributing significantly to erosion.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/abrasion-geology] In terms of a glacier, it is a similar principal; the moving of rocks over a surface wears it away with friction, digging a channel that, when the glacier moves away, is called a U-shaped valley.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/abrasion-geology] Bedload transport consists of mostly larger clasts, which cannot be picked up by the velocity of the streamflow, rolling, sliding, and/or saltating (bouncing) downstream along the bed.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/abrasion-geology] Suspended load typically refers to smaller particles, such as silt, clay, and finer grain sands uplifted by processes of sediment transport.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/abrasion-geology] Grains of various sizes and composition are transported differently in terms of the threshold flow velocities required to dislodge and deposit them, as is modeled in the Hjulström curve.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/abrasion-geology] These grains polish and scour the bedrock and banks when they make abrasive contact.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/abrasion-geology] Coastal abrasion occurs as breaking ocean waves containing a sand and larger fragments erode the shoreline or headland.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/abrasion-geology] The hydraulic action of waves contributes heavily.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/abrasion-geology] This removes material, resulting in undercutting and possible collapse of unsupported overhanging cliffs.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/abrasion-geology] This erosion can threaten structure or infrastructure on coastlines, and the impact will very likely increase as global warming increases sea level rise.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/abrasion-geology] Seawalls are sometimes built-in defense, but in many locations, conventional coastal engineering solutions such as sea walls are increasingly challenged and their maintenance may become unsustainable due to changes in climate conditions, sea-level rise, land subsidence, and sediment supply.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/abrasion-geology] Abrasion platforms are shore platforms where wave action abrasion is a prominent process.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/abrasion-geology] If it is currently being fashioned, it will be exposed only at low tide, but there is a possibility that the wave-cut platform will be hidden sporadically by a mantle of beach shingle (the abrading agent).
[src:aqueduct-bridge/abrasion-geology] If the platform is permanently exposed above the high-water mark, it is probably a raised beach platform, which is not considered a product of abrasion but may be undercut by abrasion as sea level rises.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/abrasion-geology] Glacial abrasion is the surface wear achieved by individual clasts, or rocks of various sizes, contained within ice or by subglacial sediment as the glacier slides over bedrock.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/abrasion-geology] Abrasion can crush smaller grains or particles and remove grains or multigrain fragments, but the removal of larger fragments is classified as plucking (or quarrying), the other major erosion source from glaciers.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/abrasion-geology] Plucking creates the debris at the base or sides of the glacier that causes abrasion.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/abrasion-geology] While plucking has generally been thought of as a greater force of geomorphological change, there is evidence that in softer rocks with wide joint spacing that abrasion can be just as efficient.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/abrasion-geology] A smooth, polished surface is left behind by glacial abrasion, sometimes with glacial striations, which provide information about the mechanics of abrasion under temperate glaciers.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/abrasion-geology] Much consideration has been given to the role of wind as an agent of geomorphological change on Earth and other planets (Greely & Iversen 1987).
[src:aqueduct-bridge/abrasion-geology] Aeolian processes involve wind eroding materials, such as exposed rock, and moving particles through the air to contact other materials and deposit them elsewhere.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/abrasion-geology] These forces are notably similar to models in fluvial environments.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/abrasion-geology] Aeolian processes demonstrate their most notable consequences in arid regions of sparse and abundant unconsolidated sediments, such as sand.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/abrasion-geology] There is now evidence that bedrock canyons, landforms traditionally thought to evolve only from the fluvial forces of flowing water, may indeed be extended by the aeolian forces of wind, perhaps even amplifying bedrock canyon incision rates by an order of magnitude above fluvial abrasion rates.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/abrasion-geology] Redistribution of materials by wind occurs at multiple geographic scales and can have important consequences for regional ecology and landscape evolution.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/acueducto-de-los-milagros] The **Aqueduct of the Miracles** is a Roman aqueduct in the Roman *colonia* of Emerita Augusta –present-day Mérida, Spain–, capital of the Roman province of Lusitania.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/acueducto-de-los-milagros] It was built during the first century AD to supply water from the Proserpina Dam into the city.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/acueducto-de-los-milagros] After the fall of the Roman Empire, the aqueduct fell into decay and today it is in ruins with only a relatively small section of the aqueduct bridge standing.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/acueducto-de-los-milagros] It is part of the Archaeological Ensemble of Mérida, which is one of the largest and most extensive archaeological sites in Spain and was declared a World Heritage Site by UNESCO in 1993.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/acueducto-de-los-milagros] Only a relatively small stretch of the aqueduct still stands, consisting of thirty-eight arched pillars standing 25 metres (82 ft) high along a course of some 830 metres (2,720 ft).
[src:aqueduct-bridge/acueducto-de-los-milagros] It is constructed from *opus mixtum* – granite ashlar blocks interspersed with red brick – utilising a double arcade arrangement.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/acueducto-de-los-milagros] The structure originally brought water to the city from a reservoir called the Proserpina Dam, fed by a stream called Las Pardillas, around 5 km (3.1 mi) to the north-west of Mérida.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/acueducto-de-los-milagros] It is thought to have been constructed during the 1st century AD, with a second phase of building (or renovations) around 300 AD.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/acueducto-de-los-milagros] In later centuries, the inhabitants of Mérida dubbed it the "Aqueduct of the Miracles" for the awe that it evoked.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/acueducto-de-los-milagros] The aqueduct was one of three built at Mérida, the other two being the 15 kilometres (9.3 mi) long Aqua Augusta, fed by the Cornalvo reservoir, and San Lázaro, fed by underground channels.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/acueducto-de-los-milagros] The aqueduct is preserved as part of the Archaeological Ensemble of Mérida, a UNESCO World Heritage Site.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/acueducto-de-los-milagros] In the immediate vicinity, a small Roman bridge called Puente de Albarregas runs parallel to the arcades.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/acámbaro] The municipality of Acámbaro is bordered to the north by Tarimoro and Jerécuaro, to the southeast by Tarandacuao, to the south by the state of Michoacán, and to the west by Salvatierra.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/acámbaro] The name **Acámbaro** is derived from a Purépechan term meaning *place of magueyes*.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/acámbaro] The first inhabitants of this area belonged to the Chupicuaro culture, one of the oldest in Mesoamerica.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/acámbaro] Their origin is estimated to be from 1200 B.C.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/acámbaro] In this region there have been valuable archaeological finds of ceramic that are now exhibited at the local museum.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/acámbaro] The city was founded on September 19, 1526, by the cacique Don Nicolás de San Luis Montañés, with the name *San Francisco de Acámbaro*.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/acámbaro] It was the first Spanish town in what is now the state of Guanajuato.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/acámbaro] The evangelization process was undertaken by Franciscan friars, who also constructed splendid structures that remain standing today, such as the *Templo del Hospital* (Hospital Temple), an aqueduct in the Mudéjar style (1527), and a stone bridge over the River Lerma (1750).
[src:aqueduct-bridge/acámbaro] The first bullfights on the soil of New Spain were held in Acámbaro, and the *Fuente Taurina* fountain in the city's plaza commemorates the introduction of the sport to Mexico.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/acámbaro] Acámbaro is the only city in Mexico that has a fully intact colonial-era aqueduct.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/acámbaro] The 18th century brought prosperity to Acámbaro.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/acámbaro] In that time important religious and public buildings were constructed.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/acámbaro] Several temples, bridges, and houses were left as remnants of the city's colonial architecture.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/acámbaro] An important event in the history of Mexican independence took place in Acámbaro.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/acámbaro] Don Miguel Hidalgo stayed there on October 22, 1810, and brought a ceremony that declared Acámbaro military quarters for the *Ejército Grande de América* (Grand Army of America).
[src:aqueduct-bridge/acámbaro] Hidalgo was given the title of *Generalísimo de las Américas* (Grand General of the Americas).
[src:aqueduct-bridge/acámbaro] That same day, a parade of eighty thousand insurgents took place, that demonstrated the speed of growth of the movement: one month prior on September 16 just 800 men responded to the *Grito de Dolores* and raised arms against the Spanish in Dolores Hidalgo.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/acámbaro] Because of its strategic location, Acámbaro was the key to the development of the railway in Mexico, and had a major junction, yard and shop facility for the National Railways of Mexico (The rail lines are now owned by Kansas City Southern de Mexico).
[src:aqueduct-bridge/acámbaro] Acámbaro was the home of the only full scale locomotive repair facility in Latin America that was capable of constructing steam locomotives.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/acámbaro] During 1944 Acámbaro's mechanical workshop built *La Fidelita 296*, a steam engine that is a symbol of a time in history of the *Acambarense* society.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/acámbaro] *La Fidelita* is now on display as the cornerstone exhibit of Acámbaro's railway museum.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/acámbaro] Another souvenir of Acámbaro's age of steam is a large model locomotive that sits on an elevated platform in the center of a major highway intersection east of the city.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/acámbaro] The model engine was originally intended to be placed in a church as a thanks by railway workers to the *Virgen del Refugio* (patron saint of the city) for bringing prosperity and jobs to Acámbaro, however, the model would not fit through the doorway of the church.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/acámbaro] Consequently, it was decided to mount the model outdoors.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/acámbaro] Acámbaro has been notable as a point of controversy in the field of archeology as the source of the Acámbaro figures, a collection of about 32,000 clay figurines discovered by German archaeologist Waldemar Julsrud in 1944 near the city's most prominent landmark, the *Cerro del Toro* (Bull Hill).
[src:aqueduct-bridge/acámbaro] The figures are claimed to be hoaxes, as some of the figurines resembled dinosaurs (thus implying that man and dinosaurs co-existed) and their discovery is used by some as evidence to support creationism.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/acámbaro] Many of the Julsrud finds are now on display at the *Museo Waldemar Julsrud*.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/acámbaro] Less controversial archeological artifacts are on display at the *Museo de Chupícuaro* (also known as *Museo Fray Bernardo Padilla*), documenting the history of the Chupícuaro people, and the *Museo Local de Acámbaro*, which has over 4000 relics relating to local Mesoamerican cultures.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/acámbaro] The *Museo Local* also contains paintings related to colonial Mexico and the war of independence.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/aggradation] Typical aggradational environments include lowland alluvial rivers, river deltas, and alluvial fans.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/aggradation] Aggradational environments are often undergoing slow subsidence which balances the increase in land surface elevation due to aggradation.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/aggradation] After millions of years, an aggradational environment will become a sedimentary basin, which contains the deposited sediment, including paleochannels and ancient floodplains.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/aggradation] Aggradation can be caused by changes in climate, land use, and geologic activity, such as volcanic eruption, earthquakes, and faulting.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/aggradation] For example, volcanic eruptions may lead to rivers carrying more sediment than the flow can transport: this leads to the burial of the old channel and its floodplain.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/aggradation] In another example, the quantity of sediment entering a river channel may increase when climate becomes drier.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/aggradation] The increase in sediment is caused by a decrease in soil binding that results from plant growth being suppressed.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/aggradation] The drier conditions cause river flow to decrease at the same time as sediment is being supplied in greater quantities, resulting in the river becoming choked with sediment.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/aggradation] In 2009, a report by researchers from the University of Colorado at Boulder in the journal Nature Geoscience said that reduced aggradation was contributing to an increased risk of flooding in many river deltas.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/aggradation] However, both degradation and aggradation are event driven.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/agricultural-wastewater] Nonpoint source pollution includes sediment runoff, nutrient runoff and pesticides.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/agricultural-wastewater] Point source pollution includes animal wastes, silage liquor, milking parlour (dairy farming) wastes, slaughtering waste, vegetable washing water and firewater.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/agricultural-wastewater] Many farms generate nonpoint source pollution from surface runoff which is not controlled through a treatment plant.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/agricultural-wastewater] Farmers can install erosion controls to reduce runoff flows and retain soil on their fields.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/agricultural-wastewater] Common techniques include contour plowing, crop mulching, crop rotation, planting perennial crops and installing riparian buffers.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/agricultural-wastewater] Farmers can also develop and implement nutrient management plans to reduce excess application of nutrients and reduce the potential for nutrient pollution.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/agricultural-wastewater] To minimize pesticide impacts, farmers may use Integrated Pest Management (IPM) techniques (which can include biological pest control) to maintain control over pests, reduce reliance on chemical pesticides, and protect water quality.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/agricultural-wastewater] Nonpoint source pollution from farms is caused by surface runoff from fields during rain storms.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/agricultural-wastewater] Agricultural runoff is a major source of pollution, in some cases the only source, in many watersheds.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/agricultural-wastewater] Soil washed off fields is the largest source of agricultural pollution in the United States.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/agricultural-wastewater] Excess sediment causes high levels of turbidity in water bodies, which can inhibit growth of aquatic plants, clog fish gills and smother animal larvae.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/agricultural-wastewater] Farmers may utilize erosion controls to reduce runoff flows and retain soil on their fields.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/agricultural-wastewater] Nitrogen and phosphorus are key pollutants found in runoff, and they are applied to farmland in several ways, such as in the form of commercial fertilizer, animal manure, or municipal or industrial wastewater (effluent) or sludge.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/agricultural-wastewater] These chemicals may also enter runoff from crop residues, irrigation water, wildlife, and atmospheric deposition.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/agricultural-wastewater] Pesticides are widely used by farmers to control plant pests and enhance production, but chemical pesticides can also cause water quality problems.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/agricultural-wastewater] Some pesticides have also been detected in groundwater.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/agricultural-wastewater] Farmers may use Integrated Pest Management (IPM) techniques (which can include biological pest control) to maintain control over pests, reduce reliance on chemical pesticides, and protect water quality.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/agricultural-wastewater] There are few safe ways of disposing of pesticide surpluses other than through containment in well managed landfills or by incineration.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/agricultural-wastewater] In some parts of the world, spraying on land is a permitted method of disposal.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/agricultural-wastewater] Farms with large livestock and poultry operations, such as factory farms, can be a major source of point source wastewater.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/agricultural-wastewater] In the United States, these facilities are called concentrated animal feeding operations or *confined animal feeding operations* and are being subject to increasing government regulation.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/agricultural-wastewater] Antibiotic-resistant bacteria have been found to infiltrate the water cycle from farms.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/agricultural-wastewater] Raising animals accounts for 73% of antibiotics use globally, and wastewater treatment facilities can transfer antibiotic-resistant bacteria to humans.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/agricultural-wastewater] Animal wastes from cattle can be produced as solid or semisolid manure or as a liquid slurry.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/agricultural-wastewater] The production of slurry is especially common in housed dairy cattle.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/agricultural-wastewater] Whilst solid manure heaps outdoors can give rise to polluting wastewaters from runoff, this type of waste is usually relatively easy to treat by containment and/or covering of the heap.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/agricultural-wastewater] Animal slurries require special handling and are usually treated by containment in lagoons before disposal by spray or trickle application to grassland.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/agricultural-wastewater] Constructed wetlands are sometimes used to facilitate treatment of animal wastes, as are anaerobic lagoons.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/agricultural-wastewater] Excessive application or application to sodden land or insufficient land area can result in direct runoff to watercourses, with the potential for causing severe pollution.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/agricultural-wastewater] Application of slurries to land overlying aquifers can result in direct contamination or, more commonly, elevation of nitrogen levels as nitrite or nitrate.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/agricultural-wastewater] The disposal of any wastewater containing animal waste upstream of a drinking water intake can pose serious health problems to those drinking the water because of the highly resistant spores present in many animals that are capable of causing disabling disease in humans.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/agricultural-wastewater] This risk exists even for very low-level seepage via shallow surface drains or from rainfall run-off.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/agricultural-wastewater] Some animal slurries are treated by mixing with straws and composted at high temperature to produce a bacteriologically sterile and friable manure for soil improvement.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/agricultural-wastewater] Piggery waste is comparable to other animal wastes and is processed as for general animal waste, except that many piggery wastes contain elevated levels of copper that can be toxic in the natural environment.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/agricultural-wastewater] The liquid fraction of the waste is frequently separated off and re-used in the piggery to avoid the prohibitively expensive costs of disposing of copper-rich liquid.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/agricultural-wastewater] Ascarid worms and their eggs are also common in piggery waste and can infect humans if wastewater treatment is ineffective.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/agricultural-wastewater] Fresh or wilted grass or other green crops can be made into a semi-fermented product called silage which can be stored and used as winter forage for cattle and sheep.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/agricultural-wastewater] The production of silage often involves the use of an acid conditioner such as sulfuric acid or formic acid.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/agricultural-wastewater] The process of silage making frequently produces a yellow-brown strongly smelling liquid which is very rich in simple sugars, alcohol, short-chain organic acids and silage conditioner.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/agricultural-wastewater] This liquor is one of the most polluting organic substances known.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/agricultural-wastewater] The volume of silage liquor produced is generally in proportion to the moisture content of the ensiled material.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/agricultural-wastewater] Silage liquor is best treated through prevention by wilting crops well before silage making.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/agricultural-wastewater] Any silage liquor that is produced can be used as part of the food for pigs.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/agricultural-wastewater] The most effective treatment is by containment in a slurry lagoon and by subsequent spreading on land following substantial dilution with slurry.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/agricultural-wastewater] Containment of silage liquor on its own can cause structural problems in concrete pits because of the acidic nature of silage liquor.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/agricultural-wastewater] Although milk is an important food product, its presence in wastewaters is highly polluting because of its organic strength, which can lead to very rapid de-oxygenation of receiving waters.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/agricultural-wastewater] Milking parlour wastes also contain large volumes of wash-down water, some animal waste together with cleaning and disinfection chemicals.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/agricultural-wastewater] Milking parlour wastes are often treated in admixture with human sewage in a local sewage treatment plant.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/agricultural-wastewater] This ensures that disinfectants and cleaning agents are sufficiently diluted and amenable to treatment.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/agricultural-wastewater] Running milking wastewaters into a farm slurry lagoon is a possible option although this tends to consume lagoon capacity very quickly.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/agricultural-wastewater] Land spreading is also a treatment option.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/agricultural-wastewater] Wastewater from slaughtering activities is similar to milking parlour waste (see above) although considerably stronger in its organic composition and therefore potentially much more polluting.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/agricultural-wastewater] Treatment is as for milking parlour waste.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/agricultural-wastewater] Washing of vegetables produces large volumes of water contaminated by soil and vegetable pieces.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/agricultural-wastewater] Low levels of pesticides used to treat the vegetables may also be present together with moderate levels of disinfectants such as chlorine.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/agricultural-wastewater] Most vegetable washing waters are extensively recycled with the solids removed by settlement and filtration.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/agricultural-wastewater] The recovered soil can be returned to the land.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/agricultural-wastewater] Although few farms plan for fires, fires are nevertheless more common on farms than on many other industrial premises.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/agricultural-wastewater] Stores of pesticides, herbicides, fuel oil for farm machinery and fertilizers can all help promote fire and can all be present in environmentally lethal quantities in firewater from fire fighting at farms.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/agricultural-wastewater] All farm environmental management plans should allow for containment of substantial quantities of firewater and for its subsequent recovery and disposal by specialist disposal companies.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/agricultural-wastewater] The concentration and mixture of contaminants in firewater make them unsuited to any treatment method available on the farm.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/agricultural-wastewater] Even land spreading has produced severe taste and odour problems for downstream water supply companies in the past.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/ait] The term is especially used to refer to river islands found on the River Thames and its tributaries in England.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/ait] Aits are typically formed by the deposit of sediment in the water, which accumulates.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/ait] An ait is characteristically long and narrow, and may become a permanent island should it become secured and protected by growing vegetation.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/ait] However, aits may also be eroded: the resulting sediment is deposited further downstream and could result in another ait.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/ait] A channel with numerous aits is called a braided channel.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/ait] The word derives from Old English *iggath* (or *igeth*); the root of the word, *ieg*, meaning island, with a diminutive suffix.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/ait] Although not common in 21st-century English, "ait" or "eyot" appears in J.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/ait] Tolkien's *The Lord of the Rings*, Charles Dickens's *Bleak House*, and Thackeray's *Vanity Fair*.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/ait] Joyce Cary used "eyot" in *The Horse's Mouth* – "Sun was in the bank.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/ait] Salmon trout above soaking into wash blue.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/ait] River whirling along so fast that its skin was pulled into wrinkles like silk dragged over the floor.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/ait] Ruffling under the silk-like muscles in a nervous horse.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/ait] Ruffling under my grief like ice and hot daggers".
[src:aqueduct-bridge/ait] More recently, "eyot" was used by Terry Pratchett in the first of the *Discworld* books, *The Colour of Magic*.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/ait] It also appears in *The Pope's Rhinoceros* by Lawrence Norfolk.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/ait] William Horwood used it in his 1995 novel *Toad Triumphant*.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/aqueduct-bridge] Although particularly associated with the Romans, aqueducts were likely first used by the Minoans around 2000 BCE.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/aqueduct-bridge] The Minoans had developed what was then an extremely advanced irrigation system, including several aqueducts.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/aqueduct-bridge] In the seventh century BCE, the Assyrians built an 80 km long limestone aqueduct, which included a 10 m high section to cross a 300 m wide valley, to carry water to their capital city, Nineveh.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/aqueduct-bridge] Bridges were a distinctive feature of Roman aqueducts, which were built in all parts of the Roman Empire, from Germany to Africa, and especially in the city of Rome, where they supplied water to public baths and for drinking.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/aqueduct-bridge] Roman aqueducts set a standard of engineering that was not surpassed for more than a thousand years.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/aqueduct-bridge] Navigable aqueducts, also called water bridges, are water-filled bridges to allow vessels on a waterway to cross ravines or valleys.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/aqueduct-bridge] During the Industrial Revolution of the 18th century, navigable aqueducts were constructed as part of the boom in canal-building.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/aqueduct-bridge] A notable revolving aqueduct has been made on the Bridgewater Canal.
[src:aqueduct-bridge/aqueduct-bridge] This allowed vessels to cross at high and low levels while conserving water that would be lost in the operation of locks.
